he same line, which seems fine. I should check if it requires no blank lines afterward. When it comes to Native Image, if a class is initialized at build time, it may not cover runtime dynamic access. Tests that create a map and reach the JVM could be affected. So, I need to think about how reflection works and what access may or may not be allowed during build time.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Reviewing Test Coverage and Metadata**\\n\\nI'm reflecting on build-time and runtime testing regarding native images. If a class initializes at build time, the runtime test might not cover it properly. It's crucial to keep coverage for dynamic-access classes in their own dedicated Java test files. Should I avoid using metadata since it can be untracked? \\n\\nConsidering naming conventions, I could replace numbers after a dollar sign with something like \\\"Anonymous1\\\" for clarity. I’ll also think about whether to use existing assertion libraries. For imports, I need to confirm if `sun.misc.Unsafe` is a valid dependency.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Analyzing Native Image Reflection**\\n\\nI'm focusing on the reflection configuration conditions for Native Image. It seems that reachability of metadata depends on whether certain conditions are met before using `Field.get`. This becomes active when the class is reached during analysis rather than at runtime. I'm wondering if the anonymous class is accessible when only the `ConcurrentHashMapUnsafe` class is initialized. Since the `getUnsafe` method creates the anonymous class in its catch branch, static analysis might see it, meaning the condition for `typeReached` could be satisfied. That's a positive sign!\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_A0aZSEQFxcq85CXEQRPD0E9V|fc_033c69b24efa67dd0169f8facc7b60819c861ec6673c75f84a", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "git status --short"}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 557, "output": 665, "c